This simplifies to `p.2 = q.2`.
We need to show `p.2 = q.2`.
`p.2` is `(K n).Loopwalk p.1.1 p.1.2`.
`q.2` is `(K n).Loopwalk q.1.1 q.1.2`.
We have `h_eq : p.1 = q.1` (because `s = Equiv.refl`).
So `p.1.1 = q.1.1` and `p.1.2 = q.1.2`.
We need to show that the maps `p.2` and `q.2` are equal.
`p.2` is the map `g ↦ (g.map p.1.1 p.1.2)`.
`q.2` is the map `g ↦ (g.map q.1.1 q.1.2)`.
Since `p.1.1 = q.1.1` and `p.1.2 = q.1.2`, these maps are equal.
This can be shown using `funext` and `rfl`.

