```
where `s := Equiv.refl (Fin n)` and `hs : ∀ (y : Fin n), s y = y`.

First, let's adjust the `use` statements.
We will use `s := Equiv.refl (Fin n)`.
We will use `h_eq := Equiv.refl (Fin n) x.1`.

```tactics
use Equiv.refl (Fin n)
use (Equiv.refl (Fin n) x.1)
```

Now, we need to prove the equality:
`h_eq ▸ (permMapWalk n s x.2) = x.2`
where `h_eq := Equiv.refl (Fin n) x.1` and `s := Equiv.refl (Fin n)`.

This becomes:
`(Equiv.refl (Fin n) x.1) ▸ (permMapWalk n (Equiv.refl (Fin n)) x.2) = x.2`

We can use `simp` with appropriate lemmas to simplify this.
`Equiv.refl (Fin n) x.1` simplifies to `x.1`.
`Equiv.refl (Fin n)` in `permMapWalk` also simplifies.
The lemma `simp` should be able to handle this.

```tactics
simp [Equiv.refl_apply]
```
`Equiv.refl_apply` is the lemma `Equiv.refl a x = x`.
The `simp` tactic will use this lemma to simplify the expression.
`Equiv.refl (Fin n) x.1` becomes `x.1`.
`Equiv.refl (Fin n)` in `permMapWalk` becomes `fun x => x`.
So `permMapWalk n (Equiv.refl (Fin n)) x.2` becomes `x.2`.
The goal becomes `x.1 = x.1 ▸ x.2 = x.2`. The `x.1 = x.1` part is `True`. So the goal becomes `x.2 = x.2`. `simp` will solve this.

The complete proof for reflexivity will be:
```tactics
use Equiv.refl (Fin n)
use (Equiv.refl (Fin n) x.1)
simp [Equiv.refl_apply]
```

This should correctly prove the reflexivity of the equivalence relation.

